The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all services like their partners in Western Europe.
Here, however, something is missing – a virtual operator that forces traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
The fact that the Czech operators belong to the most dear ones in Europe has already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, ČTU confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the European Commission's last steps in the area of regularising roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high in relation to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacks the competition that would really like to start the confrontation.
It may sound absurd, but here we have three mobile networks and a high coverage of over 100 %.
Instead, mobile telophony operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his network is no longer likely to have many possibilities. (Moreover, perhaps it would be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the market has led to a significant fall in prices, to which traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time, even before the arrival of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile in the market, similar voices were resounding in Britain as we have.
It has been shown, however, that there is a place for such operators and that they can really succeed.
In the end, for example, we must not go too far.
In February this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking lies the financial group Penta to which in the Czech Republic belongs, among other things U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete group-breath.
In order to be able to function effectively, it is sufficient that many less customers than a traditional operator.
They are not behind, i.e. relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low price, which is often in balance with the supply of the narrowest services
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers text messages that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows it can be a pretty good move also the bet on a group-breeding not only recently.
This operator points, so to speak, specifically at men.
"True men choose Mobilking operator that they like and that they can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be affirmed by us as in Poland.
The press spokesperson for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have much expectations.
Mobilking's ignition will happen rather in the other countries of our area," he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesperson for the financial group Penta.
He has thus indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thought.
On the contrary, try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And first it gets better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all the Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in the negotiations with some of them," says Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator may have to have it by the end of the year.
But for now around his creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the press section of Telefònika O2.
The specific nature of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the statement O2: "For now we have not noticed any business projects that are vital and beneficial to both, on which it is possible to continue to build".
He adds: "In the T-Mobil network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its 3G licence requests.
He adds Miroslav Čepický: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the context of the sharing of costs and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of the customers, to be the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet."
Competent authorities - with accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus lower profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The troubles around creation U:fon testify that when operators care about one thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was on ČTU during the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from ČTU's websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: "The environment of competition in the mobile telephony market has been strengthened little more than anything with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would put on him and above all on his high demand services."
However, the complete disinterest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies is surprising in the attitude of mobile operators.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTU which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position with regard to the whole problem.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephone market would be possible after the conclusion of the necessary infrastructure rental contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had been realized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, from the External Relations Section UUOHS, in the answer to our question.
Such a statement by the operators' representatives may not be surprising.
Instead, on the part of the office which has to defend the interests of consumers and, in addition, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Across the country where virtual operators usually work, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephony services."
But of course the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of UOOHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question as to whether it is really just a coincidence is raised on its own.
Just as the identical price of petrol for all petrols is certainly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour about this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecoms regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points .
Of course, there is the analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTU, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the network operator's agreement is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the day logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it has to be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for UUOHS it should be a minimum warning that three mobile operators will proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTU in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS is kept out of the whole thing.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of ČTU's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently approved telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that, from this, many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of UOOHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one looks
While we do not realize this, the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, some of which even exist in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists of mobile telephone services but are only partially public.
These are usually the companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the pre-established persons.
The magic lies in the fact that the company with respect to the operator appears as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar pre-sale.
"If the cases you are talking about, of which we will be interested, could be a breach of contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with this company", answered the question in question Martina Kemrová.
But it is unlikely that such an activity would reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they make a non-indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculations, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, therefore they cannot have in full of it as the usual customers of mobile phone operators "
But this should be a strange minimum at ČTU.
In addition, another question is opened for UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that UUOHS has sufficient rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions forbid it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant fall in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - too small market, too saturated limit, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in the developed countries precisely in these cases the regulatory bodies have intervened in defence not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with formal measurements and with non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and he was followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies throw each other the whole case like a boiling potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes it more than comfortable.
But let's not throw in the sponge.
If the backstage information is right and the virtual operator will really appear to us soon, the Czech mobile phone market will get back on the move.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only UUOHS could hardly remain impassive to the rejection (discriminate) of the others concerned.
And perhaps we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech hymn has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented in a solemn manner the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde Domov můj".
The new recording of the hymn was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female voice, choir step and instrumental edition.
The song is directed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the hymn reviews are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already before he told the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing the variants alone, the singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to be careful that both and the choir, have the clear diction, that the text is well understandable, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year's 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde Domov můj" was played for the first time in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
It has acquired popularity and people have spontaneously made it their own.
The first stanza of the song after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
