"People were always very happy to see Zora," Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, rocking himself in his chair on the patio on the back above Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed for long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a plaqueless grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
