Talking in your sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very anxious to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while falling asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get a scare, but it doesn't really matter much.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called sleepyloquia.
It manifests with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you have spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the baby remembers nothing.
There is no single reason why this phenomenon can be explained.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (to pee in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever levels, stress or overcrowded situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that has not yet been studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (cry, scream, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a release to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more comfortably.
Once the sleepyos appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
