The meeting - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the blood scandal in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and the protests of the population, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was late writing a report, some provinces set up a committee to design a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still trusted the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and research in the field over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he says before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the mad cow, a new manifestation of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells her that she has been president since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we absolutely did not know whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports that, when there are doubts and a serious disease could occur, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease manifests itself with a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that this disease is no doubt transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the tests of nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the presence of the virus in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against it, on which instead the tests used until then were based.
TANs have reduced the window period, i.e. from the time the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
It was possible to reduce that period to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to detect them is thus greatly diminished.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples annually, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is detected.
I believe that today we can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health, says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by an insect.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant", continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Hema-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Needs increase as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer cure, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the number of donors who on average make up only 3% of the population of Quebec acceptable as donors."
All healthy persons who have reached the age of 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where AIDS is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of scarcity are very rare.
But we must renew the members of this group of donors as they grow older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so frantic that it's hardly an hour to donate blood," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eyeball heart valves and skin that are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Héma-Québec, which operates the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion in the bank of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand of them every year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," as Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
