Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his.
No matter what the outcome of the process, the writers and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a considerable sum of money in order to organize their own defence and fight, with decidedly odd weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by virtually unfunded pockets of the mining company.
On the other hand, in these battles for unlearned weapons, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that impassions the opposition as well as to frighten anyone who dares to speak again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that he should have presented his view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada usually take place with the exchange of views and not with manganese.
It would therefore have been sufficient for the company to open its books, documents and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the financing of teams of independent researchers who could have shed light on the issue.
