Operation - rescue for Wall Street – Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the head of Congress, representatives of the Republican and Democratic leadership, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest bailout plan after the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new 700 billion US dollar version of the plan, which aims to put a stop to the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months, still needs to be ratified by the two chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses stolen for non-payments, as well as a right of inspection on salaries paid to managers of protected enterprises.
The American Secretary to the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day talks marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an effective market agreement," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
"Every decision has been taken in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the crucial point: if we had not acted in this way, invaluable discomfort and turmoil would have spilled over on the daily lives of the Americans," Republican Judd Gregg said.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The agreed time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Together with the negotiations, the two candidates for the US Presidents were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not express their discontent before the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has the credit for adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow the owners to maintain their home and the one related to salaries for managers of companies covered by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American TV screen.
Interviewed on another channel to see if he will vote in favour of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
"As far as I've read, it's something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward"
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to recover with taxpayers' money the doubtful claims, the risky and unsold assets of the US financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the explosion of a real estate bubble that led first to the collapse of mortgages at risk (loans) , then extends to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and results in the freezing of liquidity and the outflow of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in charge that blew up the first draft of a deal last week.
It seems to have come out of that blind alley since the Democrats accepted that the "toxic" assets of some companies in difficulty are only protected by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to meet everyone in Congress, a provision was added that, if the government were to face losses over the next five years due to this program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion to which 100 billion will be added if the President deems it necessary.
The deposit of 350 billion should be ratified by a further vote of Congress.
In exchange for its help, Washington will obtain shares in the protected companies that will be paid dividends in the event of profit and that will be able to resell when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the federal government will have the opportunity to delay the collection procedures for real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and start-up allowances paid to the managers of the companies involved.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to submit it to the vote of the House of Representatives, and to the vote of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be freed up.
In fact, yesterday there were several votes against the project, both in the Republican and democratic leadership.
"Obviously, Washington does not hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But certainly not to take advantage of taxpayers..
Leader of a small group in Congress called the "sceptic caucus", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents the situation in a different way, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to say: we ask Congress not to draw hasty conclusions and to examine carefully the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary when the French bank BNS Paribas announced that it would give up the purchase of its competitor, in full bankruptcy after the loss of EUR 2 billion (US$ 2.9 billion) for the crisis of real estate loans at risk in the United States.
Fortis has 85 000 employees and is one of the twenty largest banks in Europe and ten largest insurers.
"It's not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, influence and voting rights are gained in banking matters.
It is certainly something that savers and families now appreciate when times are uncertain."
During this period, at the other end of the Channel, the British government seems to be in the process of nationalising another bank in the balance sheet for the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take charge of all the loans currently under way at Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which more than 41 billion (75.5 billion dollars) are real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will be you who will buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Since the beginning of the economic crisis, Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to undergo a process of nationalization by the English government.
