The smart machine imitates the flight of the dungeon
What could be the best method of developing anti-collision technologies if not imitating the sensors of the obstacles found in nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented to CETEC in Japan, the calabrons gave the initial strategic inspiration to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic mini-car with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can scan all collisions.
Flying the bees form a personal oval space that really resembles our protective shield - Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR technology and research and development sector, explained to the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a 300 degree view in each direction.
Engineers have drawn to the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two metres away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a control to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, different from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If it weren't for that, the robot car wouldn't be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the more damaging and internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in a blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deflection cannot go upwards or downwards or diagonally, it can be only two-dimensional and in the steering direction of the wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, high energy-density lithium polymer batteries, which means that they last longer than lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot needs to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it uses only a few tens of Kb memory.
There is no need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they foresee at Nissan, can be installed within 10 years on the standard vehicles.
Further possibility of application can be represented by unification with GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding obstacles on the road leads to destination.
