Today in Paris the European Summit for Equal Opportunities began, organized this year by France with the presidency of the European Union.
Livia Járóka, MP Fidesz of the European People's Party, in a message addressed to the plenum as the main rapporteur of the Congress, drew attention to school segregation because it is the most serious legal violation that affects Roma children and, moreover, the most serious obstacle to their affirmation.
Mr Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and European Commissioner Vladimír Špidla, responsible for employment, social affairs and equal opportunities, opened the conference at the highest level.
Among those invited to the conference were governments, European social partners and representatives of major European civil and rights organisations in the context of equal opportunities.
Járóka, according to the press office of the Fidesz EP parliamentary group, pointed out, in addition to discrimination in recruitments, that Roma are excluded from the labour market in the first place because of their low level of schooling.
"Most Roma young people do not have an average level of education and as a result of poor quality elementary education only a small number of them can achieve a higher level of education."
Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in promoting human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the honourable Member, it is necessary to make these links more aware in the wider context between the Roma and non-Roma.
In fact, the sooner a Roma school starts, the more their chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase; through taxes paid for income and consumption they contribute to the nation's budget.
"The right of European citizenship of the Roma must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools" - underlined Lívia Járóka.
According to the honourable Member, the union of purpose and action of the European Union is necessary in order to speed up the process of disintegration of schools, and for this reason it is of fundamental importance to respect the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be interrupted, Roma children must be given the opportunities provided by the democratic space so that they can contribute as citizens full of the future of Europe" - asked Járóka.
In the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organised each year, since last year's Berlin meeting, is to ensure a single forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at state and European level.
