The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The New York Times of yesterday confirms this by informing us that the ongoing crisis is tearing apart the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old, moderate East Coast soul, in favour of federal institutions and the business community, and its new, conservative soul, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, especially strong in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, for the very reason, that has made itself impotently alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
This just quoted is, however, just an example of the changes, of the major changes, which the ongoing economic earthquake may foretell or already allow to see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not only here.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to function as an accelerator of incubation phenomena for a long time that in the new climate solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the realization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-survivorship in relation to a sort of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which have, yes, strong links with foreign countries, but which first and foremost involve the budgets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global, but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of play or not to have much to say: the shining test is given by the European Union which divides as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when you get to the strict it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back.
And they also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immense value, in certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis puts on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the latest developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the net, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized for a moment that our future will have to deal increasingly with those very immaterial things that are water, harvests, oil.
All things that, look a bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are nevertheless absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So that those who find themselves to be sovereign, certainly have many more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty that foreshadows a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leadership, economic species, revealed so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And together something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a disbelief, an indifference, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
In other words, there seems to be a growing belief, in large sections of the population, that before their actions are the same as the ideas of the social elites up to now, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall meaning of the term, to have made their own time and to be more and more alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the traditional political classes and structures, which manifests itself in the sudden "electoral revolutions" or in the sudden upheavals of the collective moods of these last and recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the Labour consensists in Great Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
The impression is that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it more and more difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not from today taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis invigorates, increases, acts potentially to disintegrate.
In the face of all this, talking about a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open certainly isn't.
