Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna, with 82 monosala cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And as a demonstration that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multisala cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the survival of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favour of the operators: the previous debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, ethically and morally, that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
Interestingly the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run to the shelters with the signature of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, to protect and promote the cinemas monosala both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the rules provided for there are tax relief measures for managers and public benefits in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for stopping and in some parking lots.
"It's an initiative I like," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is true, however, that in order to counteract the power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Paradise cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass before the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, there where I have lived so many shared emotions, in order not to see the signs anneritated by the dust I turn on the other side".
