When the energy comes from the waves, the big ones go down in the field.
It is an exterminated deposit, which occupies over 70% of the planet's surface and is now being discovered by the world's major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have put their eyes, and now try to put their hands, colossal like the Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil dropped around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmentalist demands and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be covered by offshore wave-movement facilities.
This amount would be twice as much as currently produced by nuclear power plants.
Plus there'd be currents and tides.
Attacks.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which signed an agreement in 2005 to build a plant in Northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away from betting on marine energy they are increasingly and among these companies that have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying the technologies on ocean energy - it has declared the spokesman of a company associated to the colossal American oilmaker to the economic newspaper Wall Street Journal - and is considering the possibility of cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission, which is needed to launch a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
It is a signal not long ago, especially if you consider that right in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and President Bush has recently launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to the Chevron, there are the Verdant Power Inc. of New York and the Ocean Power of New Jersey on the way to the energy that comes from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in the details, indicate an interest in ascension according to the observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still early, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, facilities such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
In order to produce large-scale energy, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected buoys.
The wave thrust, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such installations under design, waiting only for federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of water when there are tides turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said she has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electricity, deserves at this moment the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others that face the coast, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and previewed investments up to 35 million for 2009.
